ks for execution data. I could potentially configure the execution data to include compile information, even though compile tasks don't typically use an agent. The user probably wants code changes rather than just running tests, so I need to focus on target coverage. \\\\n\\\\nI'll think about adding a JUnit test using the Scala compiler's public API, but running that in a native image might be burdensome, especially with startup times. The test needs to be quick, ideally under 60 seconds, and needs careful consideration around class loading and macro use.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring Scala testing and reflection**\\\\n\\\\nI’m contemplating whether to use a Scala test with the public API and direct reflection to its generated lambda. I could write a test that utilizes Java reflection to access fields dynamically. However, I’m thinking that the active class may not be covered, and I might need a method accessible through `MethodHandles`. It seems I’m hitting a wall with accessing method names statically in Java.\\\\n\\\\nPerhaps using Scala's reflection with backticks might help, but typechecking doesn't recognize methods easily. There’s a possibility that TASTy might have private methods hidden from view, which could lead to compile failures.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering Java class integration in Scala**\\\\n\\\\nI'm trying to figure out if I can add a Java class in a Scala file. It seems like that’s not feasible. I want to use reflection to access a specific method, but I’m running into complications because there’s no `$` in the test class or file. While strings can have `$`, it looks like the rule only applies to names. So, I need to rethink my approach to access the method correctly.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_NtqhR5SWF9hthoyHW8WxV6Yo|fc_08901812d79efd2d016a3d9abdf64481979a2d0d5f5c2c0f8a\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.beach